<p>Variety and value remain at the core of the 2020 Hyundai Elantra&#39;s appeal. This sharp-looking compact sedan possesses a rich set of features and a lower price than comparable rivals from Honda, Mazda and Toyota. And with three engines and four trim levels, it&#39;s easy to find an Elantra to suit all tastes, whether you&#39;re primarily looking for fuel economy or something with a bit more style and spirit.</p><p>For the 2020 model year, Hyundai adds a new continuously variable automatic transmission (CVT) to many of the Elantra&#39;s trim levels. By using special components and adaptive-style shift logic, Hyundai says this new transmission provides a shifting feel similar to a standard geared transmission but with a CVT automatic&#39;s better fuel economy. We haven&#39;t yet tested this new tech and can&#39;t vouch for the claims, but it&#39;s an interesting advancement.</p>

<p>The 10th-generation Accord was a winner out of the gate in 2018, making us fall in love with Honda&#39;s midsize sedan all over again. There are no changes for the 2020 model, but that&#39;s hardly a bad thing. As it stands, the Accord is stylish and comfortable, and it hits big with utility.</p><p>Most of the Accord&#39;s competitors have been refreshed or redesigned over the past few years, but the Honda still shines in the class. On the road, the Accord is quiet and smooth, with our biggest complaint a bit of excessive tire noise at highway speeds. It&#39;s fun to drive, too, thanks to a pair of peppy engines and an available manual transmission. The car&#39;s 16.7 cubic feet of trunk space is among the biggest in the class, and the passenger area offers lots of bins and pockets for phones, sunglasses, water bottles and more.</p><p>Honda packs in a good bit of technology into the Accord, too. In addition to the standard Honda Sensing package that includes features such as adaptive cruise control, lane keeping assist and traffic sign recognition, the Accord is available with Apple CarPlay and Android Auto, LED lighting and a wireless phone charger. While you might want to look at the Mazda 6 if you desire a more premium cabin or the Kia Stinger for more exciting performance, the well-rounded Honda Accord continues to be Edmunds&#39; top-ranked midsize sedan.</p>

<p>Just about any small sedan on the market these days offers plenty of value, efficiency and safety. If all you need is basic transportation, you can pretty much just pick a name out of a hat and be satisfied. But what if you want something that&#39;s a little special? That&#39;s where the 2020 Mazda 3 comes in.</p><p>For starters, the 3 is attractively styled inside and out. It looks sophisticated and upscale, and many of the interior materials and controls have a premium feel and vibe to them. Own a Mazda 3 and your friends will probably think you spent more than you did. You also get uncommonly sporty and engaging handling, which makes the 3 fun to drive whether you&#39;re just commuting to work or taking a scenic road trip.</p><p>There are a few minor downsides. The 3 sedan comes up short on rear passenger and cargo space, for instance, and visibility to the rear is hampered by a high rear trunklid and thick roof pillars. But odds are most owners will be just fine with what 3 provides. It remains an Edmunds favorite and we&#39;re confident you&#39;ll feel the same.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>If Subaru&#39;s lifted Outback station wagon doesn&#39;t appeal to you, the brand&#39;s mechanically similar Legacy sedan might do the trick. Like the Outback, the Legacy offers standard all-wheel drive and your choice of either a 2.5-liter four-cylinder or a turbocharged 2.4-liter mill, but it forgoes the illusion of ruggedness in favor of traditional family-sedan styling. The Legacy&#39;s cabin is spacious, well-built, and comfortable, but its trunk won&#39;t hold as much as the Outback wagon&#39;s cargo hold. It shares the same marketplace with some of our favorite sedans, including the Honda Accord, the Mazda 6, and the Toyota Camry&mdash;all of which offer similar practicality, more driving verve, and sharper styling.</p>

<p>Flagship of the Volvo Cars fleet, the Volvo S80 T6 is big, mean and green, offering abundant cabin space and luxury, 272 hp, fierce performance, nimble handling and advanced low-emission engine technology. And all packaged in a car that has achieved excellent results in both European and American crash tests.</p>

<p>The Volkswagen Golf is a four-door, five-seat compact hatchback, and an originator in the segment&mdash;the first-generation model entered production in 1974. The current seventh gen Golf was introduced for the 2015 model year. Over those generations, millions of Golfs have been sold worldwide, earning wide recognition and establishing the car as a benchmark among compact hatchbacks.<br /> &nbsp;</p>
